name: Haematology
question1: What are the constituents of blood
contents:
It has 4) main components: 

  • (1) Plasma (55%) - water, electrolytes, dissolved gases (O2 and C02), plasma proteins, other dissolved substances : hormones, glucose, amino acids, coagulation proteins, lactic acid and urea 
  • Plasma proteins : contains over 500 proteins Total plasma protein concentration is 60-85 g/dL
  • Classified into : Albumin (60%), Globulins (35% alpha, beta, theta), Fibrinogen (making up 4%) 
  • Most are synthesised in the liver. Most important type of gamma-globulin is Ig which is produced by plasma cells. 
  • Alternatively can be classified according to FUNCTION: 
  • Transport proteins: Transferrin transports Iron, Ceruloplasmin transports copper, etc. 
  • Enzyme inhibitors : alpha1-antitrypsin. 
  • Coagulation: for example, fibrinogen, protein C and ATIII
  • Endocrine : for example ADH and angiotensin II
  • Immunological: IgG and IgM 
  • Mixed function: 
  • Cellular components (45%)
  • (2) Red Blood Cells, 
  • (3) White Blood Cells, and 
  • (4) Platelets. 


Plasma proteins can be used to assess nutritional status

  • Retinol binding protein (10-12hr ½ life)
  • Transthyretin (1-2 day ½ life)
  • Fibronectin (7 day ½ life); also used clinically, plays a role in enhancing phagocytosis of foreign particles
  • Transferrin (8-10 day ½ life); used clinically, although non-nutritional factors may affect
  • Albumin (30 day ½ life, 67,000Da); production decreased in stress response

In plasma: 

Albumin has many roles :

  1. Colloid oncotic pressure - responsible for 80% of IV oncotic pressure.  
  2. Transport of endogenous substances and drugs. 
  3. Free radical scavnging
  4. Acid base balance. 
  5. Plasma Ca2+ handling - negative -ve of albumin sequesters Ca2+ ions in the plasma. (reducing free Ca2+)
question2: Discuss red blood cell production and turnover
contents2:
Hb - complex polypeptide  - 4 Haem rings and an Iron atom  (O2 and CO2 transport and buffer)


  • RBC’s constitute 45% of total blood volume; this is the haematocrit, or packed cell volume 
  • The structure of the RBC is a biconcave disc
  • This enables it to have a large surface area:volume ratio and flexibility to navigate capillaries 
  • The average diameter is 7.2micro m and thickness 2 micro m at the edges 
  • RBC have no organelles so they obtain energy anaerobically.  - LIfespan of 120 days 
  • Rate of erythropoiesis is controlled by the renal hormone erythropoietin. 
  • Erythropoietin secretion is stimulated by decreased O2 delivery to the kidney
  • This may be due to decreased oxygenation of the blood, anaemia or abnormal haemoglobin 



[Red blood cells: production and turnover, haematinics, haemoglobin and its variants including abnormal haemoglobins eg thalassaemia, HbS]
contents3:
Iron 

  • Essential bio element for animals
  • Exists as Fe2+ and Fe3+ so is useful in redox reactions as it can both donate and accept electrons
  • Main uses in animals include:
  • (1) Transport of oxygen in haem groups
  • (2) Electron transfer during production of ATP 
  • Binds to transferrin in the blood
  • Also essential for bacteria to grow

Absorption

  • Absorbed in the upper small intestine (intake 10-15mg/day, 10% ABSORPTION 1-2mg/day which equals LOSS)
  • Absorption increased by vitamin C / ascorbic acid
  • Sustained release preparations improve tolerance but not efficiency of absorption

Bound by:

  • Transferrin in plasma, two ferric (Fe3+) iron atoms per molecule
  • Ferritin

Stored by: Liver (300mg-1g), Heart, Pancreas, utilisation in Myoglobin (muscle)

Utilisation in: Bone marrow (300mg) → into circulating Erythrocytes 1800mg, and Macrophages 600mg

Daily loss is 0.5-1mg in faeces

Iron Essential bio element for animals - Exists as Fe2+ and Fe3+ so is useful in redox reactions as it can both donate and accept electrons. Main uses in animals include:

  1. Transport of oxygen in haem groups
  2. Electron transfer during production of ATP
  3. Binds to transferrin in the blood
  4. Also essential for bacteria to grow


Management :

  • Ferrous sulphate has more elemental iron by mass than the gluconate formulation
  • Parenteral iron:
  • Should only be used if oral therapy is not tolerated, compliance is poor, continuing blood loss, or if have malabsorption
  • Only those with CRF have a faster response to parenteral iron than oral iron
contents5:
Von Willebrand’s disease, clopidogrel, and aspirin result in a normal platelet count but reduced activity

Platelets

  • Membrane-encapsulated fragments of megakaryocytes
  • Contain dense granules of:
  • ADP
  • ATP
  • Serotonin
  • Calcium
  • Magnesium
  • Can produce:
  • Nitric oxide
  • Prostaglandins
  • Thromboxane
  • Lifespan of 7-9 days
  • 20% found in spleen
  • May be reduced by:
  • Penicillin = binds to membrane glycoprotein = hapten = drug-induced antibody response
  • D-penicillamine
  • Thiazides
  • UFH > LMWH (HIT)
  • Aspirin
  • Alcohol
  • Quinine
  • Gold
  • Alpha-methyldopa
